        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I believe the current behavior is correct, we don't know if `readme.md` is meant to be `https://readme.md` (URL) or `./readme.md` (a local file):\n\n```\nvim.ui.open({path}, {opt})                                     *vim.ui.open()*\n    Opens `path` with the system default handler (macOS `open`, Windows\n    `explorer.exe`, Linux `xdg-open`, …), or returns (but does not show) an\n    error message on failure.\n```\n\nOn Linux the command is like `open google.com`. That said, I think the error message could be improved: instead of (current)\n```\nvim.ui.open: command failed (1): { \"open\", \"google.com\" }\n```\n\nWe could show users a more informative message from the open command:\n```diff\n vim.ui.open: command failed (1): { \"open\", \"google.com\" }\n+The file /path/to/cwd/google.com does not exist.\n+Perhaps you meant 'http://google.com'?\n```",
